      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Battle of Buffalo</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Laurence Laufer, former counsel to New York City Campaign Finance Board, says voters are shortchanged by both Hillary Clinton's and Rick Lazio's posturing on soft money (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>What you call Representative Rick A. Lazio's ''theatrical coup'' was indeed a memorable moment, but both candidates' posturing on soft money leaves voters shortchanged.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>What you call Representative Rick A. Lazio's ''theatrical coup'' was indeed a memorable moment, but both candidates' posturing on soft money leaves voters shortchanged.</p>
        <p>Fair ground rules should be set in advance. For example, candidates for New York City offices who join the city's voluntary campaign finance program must take part in specified debates. They must also accept tight restrictions on political party-paid advertisements that identify them or an opponent.</p>
        <p>Campaign finance reform can be a creative means for replacing tactical campaign posturing with the rule of law.</p>
        <p>LAURENCE LAUFER  New York, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer was general counsel to the New York City Campaign Finance Board, 1988-2000.</p>
      </block>
